@article{Logan1982,
abstract = {In 4 experiments, 12 experienced typists were instructed to stop typing when they detected a stop signal (a tone or a change in the display) to examine whether typing responses are organized into words or into single letters or letter clusters. The probability of inhibiting the last letter of a word was usually close to one and was strongly affected by word length (Exps I and II), suggesting that the unit is smaller than the word. If Ss type whole words after the stop signal, they should type fewer letters after the signal the longer the stop-signal delay because fewer letters remain to be typed. For a given stop-signal delay, they should type more letters after the signal the longer the word because more letters remain to be typed. Neither of these predictions was confirmed whether Ss typed single words or sentences, again suggesting that the unit is smaller than the word. The only exception occurred in Exp III, in which Ss tended to type "the" and the space following it before stopping. Exp IV revealed no difference between the stopping task and stopping the current sequence and beginning a new one. These 2 tasks did differ from a 3rd task in which Ss typed 2 words in succession. (17 ref) (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2006 APA, all rights reserved). {\textcopyright} 1982 American Psychological Association.},
